<br>
Has it changed raiding on test?  Well, no.  Clerics are still nailed to the cheal rotation, which they mostly hate, while druids get to dot, heal, nuke and perform a variety of tasks.  No one is trusting the druid heal enough, or perhaps their druids, to put them in the cheal chain.  So that means that everyone is just as dependent on clerics logging in to raid as they always were.<br>
<br>
Is that whining or is that raising a legitimate concern?  I guess it depends on whether you play a cleric or not or whether you have the empathy capacity of a froglok.<br>
<br>
But I can guarantee you that a greater percentage of clerics you see in the near future will be bots if Sony screws this up.  <br>
<br>
Do druids have playability issues? You betcha.  They've needed changes so they're more groupable and more necessary on raids for ages.  But to give them the raiding benefits at the expense of clerics getting groups is just going to hurt everyone.  If clerics aren't happy, they won't play clerics any longer.  I can't tell you how many ex-clerics I know.  If clerics don't play they don't come to raids.  Do guilds have so many clerics available that this isn't a problem?  I think not.<br>
<br>
Rather than calling clerics whiners and cry babies why not take a stroll around the block in their shoes and look at a slightly larger picture than out of class jealousy or whatever seems to fuel people's resentment of them.  Is it the rez you didn't get at level 11 in Oasis?  <br>
<br>
I think most clerics won't resent giving big heals to other classes as long as their viability in groups isn't diminished.  I don't think that's unreasonable.  Maybe there's some wonderful surprise that Sony hasn't revealed yet that will ease clerics fear, but it's really hard to trust them with that given their track record, especially with clerics.  Clerics have had a long history of having things taken away from them and being told to &quot;deal with it&quot;.<br>
